gs":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Dean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which has a double origin. In part it is a local name for someone who lived in a valley (Middle English <i>dene</i>, Old English <i>denu</i>) and in part an occupational name for someone who served as a dean, i.e. ecclesiastical supervisor (Latin <i>decanus</i>). The given name also sometimes represents Italian <i>Dino</i> (a short form of names such as <i>Bernardino</i>), as in the case of the American actor and singer  Dean Martin  (  1917–95 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dene","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Dean ."]},{"name":"Deane","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which has a double origin. In part it is a local name for someone who lived in a valley (Middle English <i>dene</i>, Old English <i>denu</i>) and in part an occupational name for someone who served as a dean, i.e. ecclesiastical supervisor (Latin <i>decanus</i>). The given name also sometimes represents Italian <i>Dino</i> (a short form of names such as <i>Bernardino</i>), as in the case of the American actor and singer  Dean Martin  (  1917–95 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicolas Dean ap was born about 1204, in Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Nicolas \" Dean\" ap."},"et":{"about 1204–":"umbes 1204–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1204":"1204","about 1204":"umbes 1204","1200":"1200","ABT    1240":"umbes 1240","1240":"1240","of,Morgannwg gwlad,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1204–":"noin 1204–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1204":"1204","about 1204":"noin 1204","1200":"1200","ABT    1240":"